dt-example.js:
$(document).ready(function() {
	var table = $('#example').DataTable( {
		dom: 'Bfrtip',
        ajax: '../../../../examples/ajax/data/data_10k.txt',
        columns: [
            { data: "name" },
            { data: "position" },
            { data: "office" },
            { data: "extn" },
            { data: "start_date" },
            { data: "salary" }
        ],
		buttons: ['csv', 'html', 'excel', 'pdf', 'print'],
        deferRender: true
	} );


    table.on('draw', function() {
//        $('#dtstText').val(
            table.docGen.parse(undefined, {
                //decodeEntities: false
            })
  //      );
    })

});

dt-example.info:
This is the Document Generator plug-in for Buttons. It allows for documents to be built on the server side and downloaded on the client side.

This example shows how to embed a table into a document, when that table has a large amount of data. Nodes of types `table`, `thead`, `tbody`, `tfoot`, `tr`, `th`, `td` and `string`. The structure is similar to that of an HTML table.

All of the different ways to add content and style the documents that are exported by the document builder can be found at 

* [images](/images)
* [strings](/strings)
* [styles](/styles)
* [tables](/tables)

The server-side code can be found [here](). It is powered using nodeJS.

The data can be retrieved and set using the `-api docgen.parse()` method. The structure of the JSON object is fully [documented]().

For berevity an example structure is shown below rather than showing the entire 10k rows.

